{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657603"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20578"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20578"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.13,0.09,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93709"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13455"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76919"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12502"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32132"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93709"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAtherosclerosis is a progressive disease characterised by the accumulation of lipids, inflammatory cells, and fibrous elements in the walls of medium to large arteries. The distribution pattern of these lesions within the arterial wall has important implications for diagnosis and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical distribution pattern of atherosclerotic lesions within an arterial cross-section?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eccentric lesions affecting a portion of the arterial wall","Concentric lesions affecting the entire arterial circumference","Transmural lesions extending from intima to adventitia","Segmental lesions restricted to arterial branch points","Diffuse lesions uniformly distributed throughout the arterial tree"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAtherosclerotic lesions typically appear as \u003Cstrong\u003Eeccentric lesions affecting a portion of the arterial wall\u003C/strong\u003E. This means they are asymmetrically distributed, involving only a segment of the arterial circumference rather than the entire vessel wall. This pattern creates an asymmetric narrowing of the vessel lumen when viewed in cross-section.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentric lesions affecting the entire arterial circumference\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While some advanced atherosclerotic disease may eventually involve most of the circumference, the typical pattern is eccentric, with plaques developing on one side of the vessel wall. This is in contrast to other vascular pathologies like hypertensive vascular disease, which tends to cause more concentric vessel wall thickening.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransmural lesions extending from intima to adventitia\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Atherosclerotic lesions primarily begin in the intima and may extend into the media, but they do not typically extend transmurally through all layers to the adventitia. The process begins with intimal thickening and lipid accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESegmental lesions restricted to arterial branch points\u003C/strong\u003E is partially correct but incomplete. While atherosclerotic lesions do have a predilection for areas of turbulent blood flow such as arterial bifurcations and branch points, they are not exclusively restricted to these locations. They can develop along straight segments of arteries as well, particularly where there are other risk factors present.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiffuse lesions uniformly distributed throughout the arterial tree\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Atherosclerosis has a patchy, non-uniform distribution. Certain arteries (coronary, cerebral, aorta, and lower extremity arteries) are more commonly affected than others, and even within a single artery, the distribution is typically patchy rather than diffuse.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EThe eccentric nature of atherosclerotic lesions is important clinically as it affects blood flow dynamics, imaging characteristics, and potentially treatment approaches for atherosclerotic vascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Atherosclerotic lesions are typically eccentric, affecting only a portion of the arterial wall rather than the entire circumference.","The patchy distribution of atherosclerotic plaques creates an asymmetric narrowing of the vessel lumen.","Predilection sites for atherosclerotic lesions include areas of turbulent blood flow such as arterial bifurcations."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; pages 499"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76919"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20578"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76919"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T09:04:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T09:05:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13455"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93709"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synon